{"title_page": "Vivek Agnihotri", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian director, screenwriter and author}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vivek Agnihotri\n| image              = Vivek Ranjan Agnihotri (cropped).jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| occupation         = Director, screenwriter, author\n| birth_place        = [[Gwalior]], India\n| spouse             = [[Pallavi Joshi]]\n| children           = 2\n| birth_date         = \n| education          = [[Indian Institute of Mass Communication]]\n| years_active       = \n| parents            = \n| website            = {{url|https://vivekagnihotri.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Vivek Ranjan Agnihotri''' is an Indian film director, screenwriter, and author. As of 2019, he is member of the board of India's [[Central Board of Film Certification]]. \n\nAgnihotri started his career with advertorial agencies and moved to producing and directing tele-serials; his work has been positively received. He debuted in Bollywood with the crime thriller [[Chocolate (2005 film)|''Chocolate'']] (2005) and went on to direct multiple films. Notable films that he directed are[[The Tashkent Files]] and [[Hate Story]]. In 2017, his first short film ''Mohammad and Urvashi'' won the [[Dadasaheb Phalke Award]] for best actor.\n\nAgnihotri has been frequently associated with the [[Right-wing politics|right wing]] (and [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]) by media and has been subject to controversies; he though rejects the tag and self-identifies as ''India-Wing.''\n\n== Early life and education ==\nVivek Agnihotri was born in [[Gwalior]], [[Madhya Pradesh]] to Prabhudayal Agnihotri and Ranjan Agnihotri.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nHe studied at the [[Indian Institute of Mass Communication]] before enrolling at [[Harvard Extension School]] for a Certificate of Special Studies in Administration and Management.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/interviews/director/vivek1.htm|title=\"Terrorism interests and fascinates me\":Vivek Agnihotri|date=2002-01-02|website=Indian Television Dot Com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://vivekagnihotri.com/who-is-vivek-agnihotri/|title=About|website=Vivek Agnihotri|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>{{Efn|CSS was started in 1980 as a certificate course for students with a bachelor's degree but no prior training in business or management.<ref name=\"CSS\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Gates_Unbarred.html?id=qOsSCUXn1SUC|title=\"The Gates Unbarred\": A History of University Extension at Harvard, 1910-2009|last=Shinagel|first=Michael|date=2009|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-03616-1|language=en}}</ref>{{Rp|130}} In 2007 it was converted into a full Master of Liberal Arts in Extension Studies (ALM) in management.<ref name=\"CSS\" />{{Rp|200}}}} In interviews with media, he has also mentioned [[Bhopal School of Social Sciences]] and [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]] among his ''[[Alma mater|almae matres]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tNkqp9vcVcY&t=2s|title=Risk it with Ravijot - Talk 01, Vivek Agnihotri|last=Nationalist Ravi|date=16 June 2016 |via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/entertainment/vivek-agnihotri-on-the-contrarian-kanhaiya-kumar/article8450118.ece|title=The contrarian Kanhaiya Kumar|last=Modi|first=Chintan Girish|date=2016-04-08|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-10-29|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Advertising and television serials ===\nAgnihotri started his career with the advertising agencies [[Ogilvy (agency)|Ogilvy]] and [[McCann (company)|McCann]], and served as creative director for campaigns of Gillette and Coca Cola.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> In 1994, he became involved with the directing and production of several television serials; his work was positively received.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiantelevision.com/interviews/director/vivek.htm|title='How soon the viewer flows into the story determines my success' : Vivek Agnihotri|date=2001-06-06|website=Indian Television Dot Com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/the-chocolate-lawyer/article28183638.ece|title=The chocolate lawyer|date=2005-09-19|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-12|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/one-gearing-up-to-two/article28213842.ece|title=One... gearing up to two!|date=2005-11-14|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-12|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n=== Filmography ===\n\n==== Feature films ====\nVivek debuted in [[Bollywood]] with ''[[Chocolate (2005 film)|Chocolate]]'' (2005), which is a remake of the 1995 Hollywood neo-noir crime thriller ''[[The Usual Suspects]]''. Critical reception of the movie was negative<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2005/09/16/chocolate_2005_review.shtml |title=Jaspreet Pandohar review of Chocolate (Deep Dark Secrets) (2005)|date=2005-09-11 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=4 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/shoplifted-and-shopworn/article28586523.ece|title=Shoplifted and shopworn|date=2005-09-23|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-12|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> and included accusations of [[plagiarism]]{{fact|date=April 2020}}, and the film fared poorly at box office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boxofficeindia.com/movie.php?movieid=420|title=Chocolate - Movie - Box Office India|website=boxofficeindia.com|access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/Business-meets-Bollywood/article15461380.ece|title=Business meets Bollywood|last=Dundoo|first=Sangeetha Devi|date=2011-02-28|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-12|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> ''[[Goal (2007 Hindi film)|Dhan Dhana Dhan Goal]]'' is about an all-Asian football team in the United Kingdom that wins trophies while fighting on-field discrimination and the local municipality that wants to sell the team's ground.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=FLNZDwAAQBAJ|title=The British Football Film|last=Glynn|first=Stephen|date=3 May 2018|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319777276 |pages=137|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=mFjSCwAAQBAJ|title=Bollywood in Britain: Cinema, Brand, Discursive Complex|last=Kr\u00e4mer|first=Lucia|date=2 June 2016|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA|isbn=9781501307584 |pages=74\u201378|language=en}}</ref> It received poor reception from critics<ref name=\"DDDG\">Reviews of ''Dhan Dhana Dhan Goal'':\n\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.rajeevmasand.com/uncategorized/review-dhan-dhana-dhan-goal-painfully-pointless/|title=Review: Dhan Dhana Dhan Goal\u2026 painfully pointless {{!}} Rajeev Masand \u2013 movies that matter : from bollywood, hollywood and everywhere else|website=www.rajeevmasand.com|access-date=23 October 2019}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/nov/23goal.htm|title=Goal: The Rediff Review|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=23 October 2019}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/dhan-dhana-dhan-goal/243134/0|title=Dhan Dhana Dhan Goal - Indian Express|website=archive.indianexpress.com|access-date=23 October 2019}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/dhan-dhana-dhan-goal/236217|title=Dhan Dhana Dhan Goal|last=Joshi|first=Namrata|date=10 December 2007|website=Outlook India|url-status=live |access-date=23 October 2019}}\n*{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/dhan-dhana-dhan-goal-zs6mggcb5jk|title=Dhan Dhana Dhan (Goal)|last=Critic|first=Anil Sinanan,